<subSubSection box="[189,783,626,653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1336]" box="[189,783,626,653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,351,626,652]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Flowering from September to January.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="83" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1336]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,524,662,688]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
Currently known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[892,940,663,689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">type</typeStatus>
locality in Ba Vi National park. The species grows on soil in primary tropical evergreen broad-leaved forests, on the slopes and ridges of crystalline limestone at 650–723 meters above sea level.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="83" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1336]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,318,770,796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">Etymology</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[326,354,770,796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="83">—</emphasis>
The epithet is in honor of Mr. Trinh Ngoc Bon of the Vietnamese Academy of Forest Sciences, who is passionate about studies of Vietnamese native plants and who first discovered this new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
